Stop insecure code before it ever reaches your main branch — with a workflow that runs on every pull request.

Every article I’ve written so far has been about catching security issues manually — pasting code into an AI tool, reading the response, fixing what it finds.
That works for individual review. It doesn’t work for a team.
If you’re working with even two other developers, manual security review depends entirely on someone remembering to do it. Someone gets busy. Someone assumes someone else checked. A vulnerable endpoint slips through, gets merged, and ships to production.
The fix isn’t to remind people harder. The fix is to make the check automatic and unavoidable — built directly into your pull request process, so insecure code physically cannot get merged without someone consciously overriding it.
This article is the exact process I used to build that. By the end, you’ll have a working GitHub Action that reviews every pull request for security issues and blocks the merge if it finds anything critical.

What We’re Building
A GitHub Action that:

• Triggers automatically on every pull request

• Reviews only the changed files, not your entire codebase

• Uses an AI model to analyze the diff for security vulnerabilities

• Posts the findings as a comment directly on the pull request

• Fails the check and blocks merging if critical issues are found
This runs entirely inside GitHub’s infrastructure. No servers to maintain, no manual triggering required.

