Step 6 — Add the Comment-Posting Step
Back in your workflow file, add the final steps:
- name: Post review as PR comment
if: always()
uses: actions/github-script@v7
with:
script: |
const fs = require('fs');
const comment = fs.readFileSync('review_result.md', 'utf-8'); github.rest.issues.createComment({
issue_number: context.issue.number,
owner: context.repo.owner,
repo: context.repo.repo,
body: comment
});
The if: always() ensures the comment gets posted whether the scan passes or fails — so the team sees the report either way.

Step 7 — Make Critical Issues Actually Block the Merge
Right now the script exits with a failure code, but you need to connect that to GitHub’s branch protection rules for it to actually block merging.
Go to your repository Settings → Branches → Add branch protection rule for your main branch, and enable:
☑ Require status checks to pass before merging
→ Select "security-scan" from the list
☑ Require branches to be up to date before mergingNow here’s exactly what happens on every pull request going forward:
Developer opens PR
↓
Workflow triggers automatically
↓
Changed files get scanned
↓
Comment posted with findings
↓
IF critical issues found:
→ Merge button is blocked
→ Developer must fix and push again
IF no critical issues:
→ Check passes
→ PR can be merged normally
Step 8 — Test It End to End
Create a test branch with an intentionally vulnerable endpoint:
// test-vulnerable-endpoint.js
app.post('/login', async (req, res) => {
const token = jwt.sign({ userId: req.body.userId }, 'hardcoded-secret-123');
res.json({ token });
});Open a pull request with this file. Within a minute or two, you should see:

• The workflow running in your PR’s checks tab

• A comment appearing with the security findings

• A red “X” next to the check if critical issues were found

• The merge button showing as blocked
If all four of these happen, your security gate is working correctly.

What This Actually Changes for a Team
Before setting this up, security review depended on individual discipline. Some PRs got a careful look. Others got rubber-stamped because everyone was moving fast and trusted the author.
After setting this up, every single PR gets the same baseline check, every time, with zero dependency on anyone remembering to ask for it.
This doesn’t replace human code review. A reviewer should still read the logic, understand the intent, and catch things that require actual context about the business requirements. What this catches is the category of issues that are purely mechanical — hardcoded secrets, missing validation, exposed sensitive fields — the things that don’t require human judgment, just consistent checking.
The best security process isn’t the one that relies on the most careful developer. It’s the one that works exactly the same on someone’s best day and their most exhausted, rushed, end-of-sprint day.
This workflow doesn’t care how tired anyone is. It runs the same check, every time, without exception.

Extending This Further
Once this is working, a few directions worth exploring:

• Add a severity threshold so only Critical and High block merging, while Medium and Low just get logged as comments

• Extend the file type matching to cover Python, Go, or whatever your team’s actual stack includes

• Add a Slack notification step so the team gets pinged when critical issues are found, not just a silent PR comment

• Build a simple dashboard that tracks vulnerability trends across your repository over time, using the review history
The core pattern stays the same no matter how far you take it — trigger on PR, scan the diff, report clearly, block on anything critical.
Thirty minutes to set up. A security gate that runs on every single pull request, forever, without anyone needing to remember to ask for it.

